(i) A × (B\{2})

First, we need to find the set B\{2}, which means all elements in B except for 2. So, B\{2} = {3, 4}.

Now, we can find the Cartesian product A × (B\{2}):

A × (B\{2}) = {(1,3), (1,4), (2,3), (2,4), (3,3), (3,4)}

(ii) (A × B) \(A × {2})

First, we need to find the Cartesian products A × B and A × {2}:

A × B = {(1,2), (1,3), (1,4), (2,2), (2,3), (2,4), (3,2), (3,3), (3,4)}

A × {2} = {(1,2), (2,2), (3,2)}

Now, we can find the difference (A × B) \(A × {2}), which means all elements in (A × B) that are not in (A × {2}):

(A × B) \(A × {2}) = {(1,3), (1,4), (2,3), (2,4), (3,3), (3,4)}
